German sexologists in the early 20th century used Richard B. Goldschmidt's experiments on intersex butterflies to inform their work on the criminalization of homosexuality and the study of sexual and gender diversity in several ways. When Goldschmidt published an article suggesting that his research on intersex butterflies could contribute to the ongoing debates about human homosexuality, it sparked significant interest and responses from Berlin-based sexologists affiliated with Magnus Hirschfeld, his Scientific-Humanitarian Committee, and later his Institute of Sexology. These sexologists sought to incorporate Goldschmidt's findings into their own work between 1917 and 1923. By using Goldschmidt's experiments, sexologists could argue for a more nuanced understanding of sexual and gender diversity, challenging the prevalent notion that homosexuality was solely a moral or criminal issue. Furthermore, Goldschmidt's experiments contributed to the larger question of the nature and naturalness of homosexuality and its political implications. Overall, German sexologists used Richard B. Goldschmidt's experiments on intersex butterflies to challenge prevailing perspectives on homosexuality, inform their scientific methodology, and advocate for the scientific study of sexual and gender diversity.
